ers and services in the EU calls into question the extent to which the labor market and its institutions are able to counteract negative consequences, such as downward wage pressures and abuse of workers. These essays flesh out the imbalances that unfairly disadvantage low-wage workers, shed light on their causes, and discuss possible solutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aContemporary Society. 4aSocial and Political Sciences. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh  aLabour migration - EU internal market - low waged work - migrant worker rights - labour market flexibilisation.1 aBerntsen, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCremers, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDekker, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraafland, Johan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHouwerzijl, Mijke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLange, Tesseltje de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLange, Tesseltje, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOlsson, Petra Herzfeld, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaul, Regine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRijken, Conny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoermund, Bert van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchrauwen, Annette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSiebers, Hans, econtributor.4ctb4https